The given planes are ${P_1}= 3 x - 6 y + 2 z + 5 = 0 \>\>\>\>(I)$ and ${P_2}=4 x - 12 y + 3 z - 3 = 0 \>\>\>\>(II).$ $\because$ both the planes are parallel to each other, $\dfrac{A_1}{A_2}=\dfrac{B_1}{B_2}=\dfrac{C_1}{C_2}  \implies 4 (2)-3 (3)=0 \implies 1 \neq 0.$ The plane that we are looking for should be parallel to both the above planes.  We let this unnamed plane be ${P_3}= a x + b y + c z + d=0.$ Further, since the unnamed plane bisects the angle between the planes $(I)$ and $(II),$ we get $$\dfrac{-a \times 3- b \times (-6 )- c  \times 2}{\sqrt{\text{
$a^2+b^2+c^2$}}}= \dfrac{-a\times 4 - b\times (-12 )- c \times 3}{\sqrt{\text{
$a^2+b^2+c^2}$}}.$$.  The normal vector of $P_1$ and $P_2$ are $(3,-6,2)$ and $(4,-12,3),$ respectively. The directional cosines of two vectors are computed as $$\text{cos} \, \theta_1 = \dfrac{(n_1) \cdot (\overrightarrow{PP_1})}{\left(|n_1|\over \right)}|PP_1|}  = \dfrac{v_1.0 - 6v_2 + 2v_3}{\sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2+v_3^2}}= \frac{2}{7} $$
$$\text{cos}\, \theta_2 = \dfrac{(n_2) \cdot (\overrightarrow{PP_2})}{\left( |n_2|\over \right)}|PP_2|}  = \dfrac{4v_1 - 12v_2 + 3v_3}{\sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2+v_3^2}}= \frac{1}{7}$$
Also, the distance of the plane from the origin is $\frac{ d}{\sqrt{A^2+B^2+C^2}}.$ Since the distance is constant, we write $$|d_1|=|d_2|\implies \left|\dfrac{d}{5}\right|=\dfrac{d}{2}$$
Also, the bisecting plane bisects the angle between the given planes, hence it passes through the line of intersection of the two planes. So, we can take $\vec r\times\vec r_1\cdot [r_1\times r_2\times\vec r_2]=0$ for some $\vec r$. $\vec r_1=3 \hat i-6\hat j+2\hat k\cdot$ Now what is $d$?osphere circumference isn't defined here. Applying the above formulas we find $$P_3=3 x - 6 y+ 2 z + 5-\dfrac52=0$$ Hence the correct answer is $ [2x − 4y +z +4 = 0 ]$ [Answer]

